    <h1 class="text-center">Alegrias in C Major</h1>
    <div class="col-sm-12">
      <p> The <span class="italic">alegrías</span> are the dominant <span class="italic">cante</span> of a group of
        <span class="italic">cantes</span> categorized as <span class="italic">cantiñas</span>, developed in Cádiz from
        the more ancient <span class="italic">soleares</span> and <span class="italic">jaleos</span>. The rhytmical
        count and accentuation of the <span class="italic">soleares</span> and the <span class="italic">alegrías</span>
        are identical, although the <span class="italic">alegrías</span> are faster, and their chord structure stresses
        the bright major rather than the melancholy minor chords of the <span class="italic">soleares</span>. <p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="container">
  <div class="jumbotron">
    <h1 class="text-center">Bulerias in A minor</h1>
    <p> The <span class="italic">bulerias</span> occupy a special and supreme position in the world of flamenco. They
      are its most festive form, constantly undergoing change, wide open to spontaneity, full of humor and yet
      intrinsically majestic, all of which combine to make them flamenco´s run away festive favorite. </p>

    <p>Due to the extreme adaptability of the <span class="italic">bulerias</span>, they are flamenco´s most badly
      abused <span class="italic">cante</span>, having to suffer never ending mixtures both international and national.
      They are one of the most difficult dances to dominate, as a great deal of <span class="italic">gracia</span> and
      sense of rhythm are essential. They are also the most technically intricate and difficult flamenco form for the
      guitarist, especially if they are played at a ridiculously fast pace.<p>

        <p>All of flamenco is made up of little sections and this is no exception. Here you can take these parts and mix
          them or add them into your own bulerias or use them together. </p>

  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <div class="jumbotron">
    <h1 class="text-center">Fandangos</h1>
    <p> The <span class="italic">fandangos grandes</span> are one of the most widely sung, and badly abused <span
        class="italic">cantes</span> of all flamenco. Every singer with the minimum of pretentions attempts the <span
        class="italic">fandangos grandes</span>; but the <span class="italic">grandes</span>, sung as they should be,
      are not a <span class="italic">cante</span> for the run of the mill singer. </p>

    <p> The origin of the category “fandangos”, which includes the <span class="italic">grandes</span> and the <span
        class="italic">fandanguillos</span> (also called fandangos de Huelva), is thought to have been in the <span
        class="italic">jota</span> country of northern Spain. The original <span class="italic">fandangos</span> were
      lively and danceable, accompanied by guitars, castanets, tambourines, and violins. In time one branch of the <span
        class="italic">fandangos</span> took on more serious aspects, chiefly because of the influence of Arabic
      stylings, and grew away from the original <span class="italic">fandangos</span>.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="container">
  <div class="jumbotron">
    <h1 class="text-center">Granaínas</h1>
    <p> The <span class="italic">granaínas</span> are an adaption of the <span class="italic">fandangos grandes</span>
      which have been strongly influenced by the Moors, rulers of Granada for eight centuries. They have, therefore,
      developed a more discordant, Oriental quality than the <span class="italic">fandangos grandes</span>. They are a
      free <span class="italic">cante</span> without a determined <span class="italic">compás</span>. The term
      “granainás” is an abbreviation of “granadinas”, which means to say “songs from Granada”. </p>

  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <div class="jumbotron">
    <h1 class="text-center">Guajiras</h1>
    <p>- <span class="italic">Cante, baile</span> and <span class="italic">toque chico.</span></p>
    <p> The <span class="italic">guajiras</span> are a flamenco version of a Cuban rhythm of the same name. They are
      said to have been brought to Spain in the XVI century by the Spanish soldiers returning from the conquests. Most
      of their versus deal with Cuba and the Cubans, usually in a light vein. They are rhythmically similar to the other
      flamenco forms influenced by the new world. <p>

  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <div class="jumbotron">
    <h1 class="text-center"> Malagueñas</h1>
    <p>- <span class="italic">Cante</span> and <span class="italic">toque intermedio</span>, not danced.</p>
    <p>The province of Malaga has developed its own very personal world of flamenco. Like so many <span
        class="italic">cantes</span>, the <span class="italic">malagueñas</span> are directly decendended from the <span
        class="italic">fandangos grandes</span>, and, like them, are a free <span class="italic">cante</span> without a
      determined <span class="italic">compas</span>.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
