      <h1 class="text-center">Siguiriyas</h1>
      <p>- <em>Cante, baile</em> and <em>toque grande</em>.</p>
      <p>Most <em>aficionados</em> agree that the <em>siguiriyas</em> are the most profoundly emotional element of
        flamenco. To the uninitiated the <em>compas</em> appears difficult and vague, but in reality is composed of
        twelve beats, as are the <em> soleares, alegrias, bulerias, fandanguillos, </em> and many other rhythmical
        flamenco forms.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="jumbotron">
      <p> The word <em>solea</em> is a gypsy abbreviation of <em>soledad</em>. The word <em>soleares</em> is an improper
        pluralization of “soledad”. Both “soleares” and “solea” signify loneliness and can be used interchangeably. The
        <em>soleares</em> has been described as the “mother of the cante”. There is no doubt that they are the central
        figure around which all of flamenco revolves. </p>

      <p>There are countless theories concerning the antiquity and development of the <em>soleares</em>. It is thought
        that in some form, probably not that which we know today, the <em>soleares</em> have existed for many centuries.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="jumbotron">
      <h1 class="text-center">Solea por Buleria</h1>
      <p>Solea por Buleria can be thought of as between a Solea and a Bulerias. Some are adament that it should be
        called Buleria por Solea.</p>

    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="jumbotron">
      <h1 class="text-center">Tangos</h1>
      <p> The <em>tangos</em>, considered one of the oldest and most basic gypsy <em>cantes</em>, have an unknown
        origin, but theories abound. The <em>tangos</em> are also called <span class="italic">tientos canasteros</span>,
        which means to say <em>gypsy tientos</em> (<em>canasteros</em> is a flamenco term for “wandering gypsy”, and
        also, less likely in this case, for “basket weavers”), and has led some to think that the <em>tangos</em> came
        about as merely a more gypsified version of the <em>tientos</em>. </p>

    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="jumbotron">
      <h1 class="text-center">Tarantas</h1>
      <p> The <em>tarantas</em> are basically a <em>cante</em> of miners. Thought to have originated in the province of
        Almería, they spread to wherever there are mines in southern Spain: in particular, to the provinces of Jaén
        (Linares) and Murcia. They are a resigned <em>cante</em>, well reflecting the atmosphere in which they
        developed. <p>
          <p>The <em>tarantas</em> are a <em>cante</em> free from <em>compás</em>. They are descended from the
            <em>fandangos grandes</em>, but with a far more discordant Moorish influence. Their verses usually reflect
            mining themes.</p>

    </div>
  </div>
